Since more than 80 % of the State’s revenue is derived from this sector, there was an urgent need to prioritise the development of this industry that comes from the endogenous culture, hopes and desires of people in the field. This satisfied the bounds for participation in the design process of the National Policy for the Development of Culture to make culture a viable contributor to sustainability and economic growth.

Challenges

Grenada is developing into an internationally-respected tourism destination with splendid beaches, great cuisine and an enriching history. The island is still blessed with immense reserves of natural, cultural and historical assets, but the decision has been made to exploit these with social conscience and tolerance. The Grenada Fund for Sustainable Development (GFSD), a cultural organisation for the development of culture and promotion of arts in Grenada, was created to foster sustainable and responsible tourism. In knowing that the development of tourism brings the risk of preserving too much of the existing cultural and natural heritage, thereby losing its essence, the GFSD was established to safeguard and protect this cultural heritage.

On a larger scale, the Government of Grenada considers Caribbean citizenship, interconnectivity and innovation as one of the priorities for the National Policy for the Development of Culture (2005-2015). The latter has already been implemented and used to encourage partnerships for the public and private sectors.

The National Development Plan (BDCP) is also deeply involved with the promotion of sustainable development
